1105 // Lightweight std::vector<> like class to avoid dragging dependencies (also: windows implementation of STL with debug enabled is absurdly slow, so let's bypass it so our code runs fast in debug).
1106 // Our implementation does NOT call C++ constructors/destructors. This is intentional and we do not require it. Do not use this class as a straight std::vector replacement in your code!
1107 template<typename T>
1108 class ImVector
1109 {
1110 public:
1111  int Size;
1112  int Capacity;
1113  T* Data;
1114 
1115  typedef T value_type;
1116  typedef value_type* iterator;
1117  typedef const value_type* const_iterator;
1118 
1119  inline ImVector() { Size = Capacity = 0; Data = NULL; }
1120  inline ~ImVector() { if (Data) ImGui::MemFree(Data); }
1121 
1122  inline bool empty() const { return Size == 0; }
1123  inline int size() const { return Size; }
1124  inline int capacity() const { return Capacity; }
1125 
1126  inline value_type& operator[](int i) { IM_ASSERT(i < Size); return Data[i]; }
1127  inline const value_type& operator[](int i) const { IM_ASSERT(i < Size); return Data[i]; }
1128 
1129  inline void clear() { if (Data) { Size = Capacity = 0; ImGui::MemFree(Data); Data = NULL; } }
1130  inline iterator begin() { return Data; }
1131  inline const_iterator begin() const { return Data; }
1132  inline iterator end() { return Data + Size; }
1133  inline const_iterator end() const { return Data + Size; }
1134  inline value_type& front() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[0]; }
1135  inline const value_type& front() const { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[0]; }
1136  inline value_type& back() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[Size - 1]; }
1137  inline const value_type& back() const { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[Size - 1]; }
1138  inline void swap(ImVector<T>& rhs) { int rhs_size = rhs.Size; rhs.Size = Size; Size = rhs_size; int rhs_cap = rhs.Capacity; rhs.Capacity = Capacity; Capacity = rhs_cap; value_type* rhs_data = rhs.Data; rhs.Data = Data; Data = rhs_data; }
1139 
1140  inline int _grow_capacity(int sz) const { int new_capacity = Capacity ? (Capacity + Capacity/2) : 8; return new_capacity > sz ? new_capacity : sz; }
1141 
1142  inline void resize(int new_size) { if (new_size > Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(new_size)); Size = new_size; }
1143  inline void resize(int new_size, const T& v){ if (new_size > Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(new_size)); if (new_size > Size) for (int n = Size; n < new_size; n++) Data[n] = v; Size = new_size; }
1144  inline void reserve(int new_capacity)
1145  {
1146  if (new_capacity <= Capacity)
1147  return;
1148  T* new_data = (value_type*)ImGui::MemAlloc((size_t)new_capacity * sizeof(T));
1149  if (Data)
1150  memcpy(new_data, Data, (size_t)Size * sizeof(T));
1151  ImGui::MemFree(Data);
1152  Data = new_data;
1153  Capacity = new_capacity;
1154  }
1155 
1156  // NB: &v cannot be pointing inside the ImVector Data itself! e.g. v.push_back(v[10]) is forbidden.
1157  inline void push_back(const value_type& v) { if (Size == Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(Size + 1)); Data[Size++] = v; }
1158  inline void pop_back() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); Size--; }
1159  inline void push_front(const value_type& v) { if (Size == 0) push_back(v); else insert(Data, v); }
1160 
1161  inline iterator erase(const_iterator it) { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data+Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; memmove(Data + off, Data + off + 1, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off - 1) * sizeof(value_type)); Size--; return Data + off; }
1162  inline iterator insert(const_iterator it, const value_type& v) { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it <= Data+Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; if (Size == Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(Size + 1)); if (off < (int)Size) memmove(Data + off + 1, Data + off, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off) * sizeof(value_type)); Data[off] = v; Size++; return Data + off; }
1163  inline bool contains(const value_type& v) const { const T* data = Data; const T* data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data++ == v) return true; return false; }
1164 };

1166 // Helper: execute a block of code at maximum once a frame. Convenient if you want to quickly create an UI within deep-nested code that runs multiple times every frame.
1167 // Usage:
1168 // static ImGuiOnceUponAFrame oaf;
1169 // if (oaf)
1170 // ImGui::Text("This will be called only once per frame");
1171 struct ImGuiOnceUponAFrame
1172 {
1173  ImGuiOnceUponAFrame() { RefFrame = -1; }
1174  mutable int RefFrame;
1175  operator bool() const { int current_frame = ImGui::GetFrameCount(); if (RefFrame == current_frame) return false; RefFrame = current_frame; return true; }
1176 };

1232 // Helper: Simple Key->value storage
1233 // Typically you don't have to worry about this since a storage is held within each Window.
1234 // We use it to e.g. store collapse state for a tree (Int 0/1), store color edit options.
1235 // This is optimized for efficient reading (dichotomy into a contiguous buffer), rare writing (typically tied to user interactions)
1236 // You can use it as custom user storage for temporary values. Declare your own storage if, for example:
1237 // - You want to manipulate the open/close state of a particular sub-tree in your interface (tree node uses Int 0/1 to store their state).
1238 // - You want to store custom debug data easily without adding or editing structures in your code (probably not efficient, but convenient)
1239 // Types are NOT stored, so it is up to you to make sure your Key don't collide with different types.
1240 struct ImGuiStorage
1241 {

1243  {
1244  ImGuiID key;
1245  union { int val_i; float val_f; void* val_p; };
1246  Pair(ImGuiID _key, int _val_i) { key = _key; val_i = _val_i; }
1247  Pair(ImGuiID _key, float _val_f) { key = _key; val_f = _val_f; }
1248  Pair(ImGuiID _key, void* _val_p) { key = _key; val_p = _val_p; }
1249  };
1250  ImVector<Pair> Data;
1251 
1252  // - Get***() functions find pair, never add/allocate. Pairs are sorted so a query is O(log N)
1253  // - Set***() functions find pair, insertion on demand if missing.
1254  // - Sorted insertion is costly, paid once. A typical frame shouldn't need to insert any new pair.
1255  void Clear() { Data.clear(); }
1256  IMGUI_API int GetInt(ImGuiID key, int default_val = 0) const;

1263  IMGUI_API void SetVoidPtr(ImGuiID key, void* val);
1264

1266  // - References are only valid until a new value is added to the storage. Calling a Set***() function or a Get***Ref() function invalidates the pointer.

1381 // Helper: Manually clip large list of items.
1382 // If you are submitting lots of evenly spaced items and you have a random access to the list, you can perform coarse clipping based on visibility to save yourself from processing those items at all.
1383 // The clipper calculates the range of visible items and advance the cursor to compensate for the non-visible items we have skipped.
1384 // ImGui already clip items based on their bounds but it needs to measure text size to do so. Coarse clipping before submission makes this cost and your own data fetching/submission cost null.
1385 // Usage:
1386 // ImGuiListClipper clipper(1000); // we have 1000 elements, evenly spaced.
1387 // while (clipper.Step())
1388 // for (int i = clipper.DisplayStart; i < clipper.DisplayEnd; i++)
1389 // ImGui::Text("line number %d", i);
1390 // - Step 0: the clipper let you process the first element, regardless of it being visible or not, so we can measure the element height (step skipped if we passed a known height as second arg to constructor).
1391 // - Step 1: the clipper infer height from first element, calculate the actual range of elements to display, and position the cursor before the first element.
1392 // - (Step 2: dummy step only required if an explicit items_height was passed to constructor or Begin() and user call Step(). Does nothing and switch to Step 3.)
1393 // - Step 3: the clipper validate that we have reached the expected Y position (corresponding to element DisplayEnd), advance the cursor to the end of the list and then returns 'false' to end the loop.
1394 struct ImGuiListClipper
1395 {
1396  float StartPosY;
1397  float ItemsHeight;
1398  int ItemsCount, StepNo, DisplayStart, DisplayEnd;
1399 
1400  // items_count: Use -1 to ignore (you can call Begin later). Use INT_MAX if you don't know how many items you have (in which case the cursor won't be advanced in the final step).
1401  // items_height: Use -1.0f to be calculated automatically on first step. Otherwise pass in the distance between your items, typically GetTextLineHeightWithSpacing() or GetFrameHeightWithSpacing().
1402  // If you don't specify an items_height, you NEED to call Step(). If you specify items_height you may call the old Begin()/End() api directly, but prefer calling Step().
1403  ImGuiListClipper(int items_count = -1, float items_height = -1.0f) { Begin(items_count, items_height); } // NB: Begin() initialize every fields (as we allow user to call Begin/End multiple times on a same instance if they want).
1404  ~ImGuiListClipper() { IM_ASSERT(ItemsCount == -1); } // Assert if user forgot to call End() or Step() until false.
1405 
1406  IMGUI_API bool Step(); // Call until it returns false. The DisplayStart/DisplayEnd fields will be set and you can process/draw those items.
1407  IMGUI_API void Begin(int items_count, float items_height = -1.0f); // Automatically called by constructor if you passed 'items_count' or by Step() in Step 1.
1408  IMGUI_API void End(); // Automatically called on the last call of Step() that returns false.
1409 };
